Besides the above, P. B. Watson, in his Life of Marcus Aurelius, London, 1884, gives versions of several passages | from the Correspondence, but he is an unsafe guide as to | Fronto’s meaning, his knowledge of Latin being inadequate. | Amore scholarly contribution to the same subject is that of Hastings Crossley in his Fourth Book of the Meditations | of Marcus Awrelius, London, 1882, an appendix to which contains a number of select passages from the letters admirably Englished with a running comment.

_ Finally, Robinson Ellis published at Oxford in 1904 a lecture on The Correspondence of Frunto and Marcus Aurelius, | It translates a considerable number of passages from various | parts of the work with connecting comments.


