cannot but say so. For I am in love and this, if nothing else, ought, I think, verily to be allowed to lovers, that they should have greater joy in the triumph of their loved ones. Ours, then, is the triumph, ours, I say. Isit ... . preferable to talk philosophy under ceilings rather than under plane- trees, within the city bounds than without its walls, ‘scorning delights than with Lais herself sitting at our side or sharing our home? Nor can I “make a east” which to beware of more, the law which an orator! of our time has laid down about this Lais, or my master’s dictum about Plato.

