.... unless speech is graced by dignity of lan- guage, it becomes downright impudent and indecent. In fine you too, when you have had to speak in the Senate or harangue the people, have never used a far-fetched word,! never an unintelligible or unusual figure, as knowing that a Caesar’s eloquence should be like the clarion not like the clarionet, in which there is less resonance and more difficulty.

