Maecianus! was pressing, and it was right that your brother should return to you in good time. I beseech you, therefore, if you find any solecism or confusion of thought or shaky letter herein, put it down to haste. For though 1 am desperately fond of you as a friend, at the same time | must not forget that I ought to shew no less respect to my master than love to my friend. Farewell, my Fronto, dearest and beyond all things sweetest to me. 4, The Sota? of Ennius, which you have returned, seems to be on clearer paper, in a more handsome volume and a prettier hand than before. Let Grac- chus ὃ bide with the cask of new wine until we come. There is no risk of Gracchus fermenting out‘ meanwhile along with the wine. Fare ever well, my sweetest soul.

