T ? 154-156 a.p. o my Lord.

That you may keep many birthdays of your children with all happiness, the pride of your ‘parents, the darling of the people, the beloved of your friends, worthy of your fortune, your lineage, and your station, gladly would I give my whole life, not that meagre portion of it only that now remains to me, but also what I have already lived, if in any way it could -be restored to me entire, and expended as the repayment of a debt for the benefit of your- self and your children. If I could walk with com- fort, this were the day on which I would wish among the first! to embrace you; but I must, as you see, make my feet some concession, since they have not much procession in them. I am thinking of trying waters. If I come any nearer a decision, I will let you know. Farewell, my sweetest Lord. Give your Faustina a message from me and congratulate her? and kiss our little ladies in my name and, as

I always do, their feet and hands as well. Greet

your Lady.®

