1. Even he would have no lack of plausible argu- ments who, in answer to the first of the propositions submitted by you, should object that private conduct ᾿ ought not to conform to that of states. For we shall find many customs and usages publicly estab- lished in cities and privately practised by individuals to be dissimilar. You can easily convince yourself of this by looking at the litigation and disputes between public bodies and individuals, wherein neither the venue of the court nor the number of the judges nor the order of the pleas and summonses nor the allowance of time for the speakers nor the penalties of conviction are the same, but there is


